1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,143
A good AI answer can still arrive too
early.

2
00:00:04,223 --> 00:00:06,064
You ask a question.

3
00:00:06,144 --> 00:00:11,667
The model gives a fluent paragraph, a
clean plan, maybe even a

4
00:00:11,747 --> 00:00:12,947
reasonable recommendation.

5
00:00:13,027 --> 00:00:14,868
It feels like progress.

6
00:00:14,948 --> 00:00:20,472
But sometimes the answer is solving a
question you have not finished

7
00:00:20,552 --> 00:00:21,752
asking.

8
00:00:21,832 --> 00:00:27,355
This video is about slowing the first
answer down just enough to

9
00:00:27,435 --> 00:00:31,117
keep the human parts of the decision
visible.

10
00:00:31,197 --> 00:00:36,721
By the end, you will have one prompt you
can reuse before

11
00:00:36,801 --> 00:00:38,642
any important AI answer.

12
00:00:38,722 --> 00:00:40,563
It checks three things:

13
00:00:40,643 --> 00:00:42,024
Goal. Grounding. Ownership.

14
00:00:42,104 --> 00:00:44,866
What are we trying to do?

15
00:00:44,946 --> 00:00:47,707
What facts would change the answer?

16
00:00:47,787 --> 00:00:51,470
And what parts are still mine to choose?

17
00:00:51,550 --> 00:00:55,232
Think of the model as a bright worktable.

18
00:00:55,312 --> 00:00:58,534
It can lay out options and tradeoffs.

19
00:00:58,614 --> 00:01:02,658
But the worktable should not decide what
the work is for.

20
00:01:02,658 --> 00:01:04,929
Start with a small example.

21
00:01:05,009 --> 00:01:06,209
You ask:

22
00:01:06,289 --> 00:01:09,015
Should I redesign this onboarding page?

23
00:01:09,095 --> 00:01:14,546
The model might say: simplify the page,
reduce friction, test a clearer

24
00:01:14,626 --> 00:01:15,826
button.

25
00:01:15,906 --> 00:01:19,994
Useful, maybe. But it is answering a
half-built question.

26
00:01:20,074 --> 00:01:25,525
Does “better” mean more signups, fewer
confused users, fewer support tickets, or

27
00:01:25,605 --> 00:01:27,876
a more honest first impression?

28
00:01:27,956 --> 00:01:29,773
Those are different goals.

29
00:01:29,853 --> 00:01:35,304
If you do not name the goal, the model may
quietly name

30
00:01:35,384 --> 00:01:36,747
it for you.

31
00:01:36,827 --> 00:01:42,278
So the first checkpoint is Goal: what am I
actually trying to

32
00:01:42,358 --> 00:01:43,720
decide or create?

33
00:01:43,800 --> 00:01:47,434
Not just “make this better.” Better for
whom?

34
00:01:47,514 --> 00:01:49,331
Better by what measure?

35
00:01:49,411 --> 00:01:51,228
Better at what cost?

36
00:01:51,308 --> 00:01:56,759
This applies beyond product work: a
purchase, a job choice, a family

37
00:01:56,839 --> 00:01:58,656
plan, a hard email.

38
00:01:58,736 --> 00:02:03,684
Once the target is visible, the model can
help without inventing the

39
00:02:03,764 --> 00:02:03,684
game.

40
00:02:03,684 --> 00:02:06,115
The second checkpoint is Grounding.

41
00:02:06,195 --> 00:02:10,085
Ask: what real-world facts would change
the answer?

42
00:02:10,165 --> 00:02:15,999
If the model recommends a redesign, what
would make that recommendation stronger

43
00:02:16,079 --> 00:02:17,279
or weaker?

44
00:02:17,359 --> 00:02:21,249
Maybe users drop off at the second step.

45
00:02:21,329 --> 00:02:25,219
Maybe support tickets mention the same
confusing sentence.

46
00:02:25,299 --> 00:02:28,702
Maybe people hesitate over a price detail.

47
00:02:28,782 --> 00:02:33,158
Or maybe the page is not the real problem.

48
00:02:33,238 --> 00:02:38,100
So instead of only asking, “explain your
reasoning,” try asking:

49
00:02:38,180 --> 00:02:41,098
What evidence would change your
recommendation?

50
00:02:41,178 --> 00:02:45,554
Separate what you know from what you are
assuming.

51
00:02:45,634 --> 00:02:49,782
That turns the answer into a checklist for
reality.

52
00:02:49,782 --> 00:02:54,170
This is a small habit, not a safety
guarantee.

53
00:02:54,250 --> 00:03:00,101
Decision-support researchers have long
studied cases where people lean too hard
on

54
00:03:00,181 --> 00:03:01,381
automated recommendations.

55
00:03:01,461 --> 00:03:07,313
In some human-AI studies, explanations
changed how people relied on a system.

56
00:03:07,393 --> 00:03:12,756
They did not reliably help people spot
which recommendations were correct.

57
00:03:12,836 --> 00:03:18,200
So the point is not: ask for an
explanation and relax.

58
00:03:18,280 --> 00:03:24,131
The point is: make the goal, assumptions,
evidence, and value choices visible

59
00:03:24,211 --> 00:03:26,424
before the advice feels settled.

60
00:03:26,424 --> 00:03:28,675
The third checkpoint is Ownership.

61
00:03:28,755 --> 00:03:34,158
Some parts of a decision are not facts the
model can discover.

62
00:03:34,238 --> 00:03:37,839
They depend on values, context,
responsibility, and risk.

63
00:03:37,919 --> 00:03:39,270
Suppose you write:

64
00:03:39,350 --> 00:03:44,753
Draft an email telling a collaborator I am
unhappy that the timeline

65
00:03:44,833 --> 00:03:46,033
is slipping.

66
00:03:46,113 --> 00:03:49,264
The model can produce a polished email.

67
00:03:49,344 --> 00:03:53,846
But it does not know what you want to
protect.

68
00:03:53,926 --> 00:03:59,329
Do you want to repair trust, set a
boundary, get a new

69
00:03:59,409 --> 00:04:01,210
date, or document accountability?

70
00:04:01,290 --> 00:04:05,792
A gentle version may preserve warmth but
blur the boundary.

71
00:04:05,872 --> 00:04:10,374
A firm version may create clarity but
raise the temperature.

72
00:04:10,454 --> 00:04:13,155
A direct version may do both.

73
00:04:13,235 --> 00:04:16,837
The model can show versions side by side.

74
00:04:16,917 --> 00:04:20,969
You choose what you are willing to stand
behind.

75
00:04:21,049 --> 00:04:22,850
A better request is:

76
00:04:22,930 --> 00:04:28,332
Before drafting, list the possible goals
of this message and the relationship

77
00:04:28,412 --> 00:04:29,763
risks of each.

78
00:04:29,843 --> 00:04:33,445
Then give three versions: gentle, direct,
and firm.

79
00:04:33,525 --> 00:04:36,226
Separate tone choices from factual claims.

80
00:04:36,306 --> 00:04:40,358
Now the model is doing work on the table.

81
00:04:40,438 --> 00:04:43,290
You are still responsible for the
decision.

82
00:04:43,290 --> 00:04:46,676
Here is the whole habit as one prompt:

83
00:04:46,756 --> 00:04:50,565
Before answering, help me keep ownership
of this decision.

84
00:04:50,645 --> 00:04:51,845
1.

85
00:04:51,925 --> 00:04:55,311
Restate the goal you think I am pursuing.

86
00:04:55,391 --> 00:04:56,591
2.

87
00:04:56,671 --> 00:05:00,903
List the facts or evidence that would
change your answer.

88
00:05:00,983 --> 00:05:02,183
3.

89
00:05:02,263 --> 00:05:06,918
Identify which parts depend on my values,
context, or risk tolerance.

90
00:05:06,998 --> 00:05:09,961
Then give advice, separating assumptions
from recommendations.

91
00:05:10,041 --> 00:05:13,004
That does not make the model correct.

92
00:05:13,084 --> 00:05:16,469
But it gives you three places to
intervene.

93
00:05:16,549 --> 00:05:19,512
If the goal is wrong, correct it.

94
00:05:19,592 --> 00:05:23,401
If the evidence is missing, go look for
it.

95
00:05:23,481 --> 00:05:27,156
If the answer depends on values, stop
pretending it is only a

96
00:05:27,236 --> 00:05:27,156
technical question.

97
00:05:27,156 --> 00:05:32,017
Try it on the next AI request that
actually matters.

98
00:05:32,097 --> 00:05:35,013
Paste the prompt before your question.

99
00:05:35,093 --> 00:05:40,926
Let the model fill in the goal, the
evidence, and the value-dependent

100
00:05:41,006 --> 00:05:42,206
parts.

101
00:05:42,286 --> 00:05:47,147
Then edit those three answers before you
accept the recommendation.

102
00:05:47,227 --> 00:05:49,171
Wrong goal? Fix it.

103
00:05:49,251 --> 00:05:53,626
Missing evidence? Look for it or lower
your confidence.

104
00:05:53,706 --> 00:05:58,566
Value tradeoff? Pause. Smooth prose cannot
choose that for you.

105
00:05:58,646 --> 00:06:04,479
That is the difference between using AI to
think with you and

106
00:06:04,559 --> 00:06:07,734
letting it quietly finish the thinking for
you.

107
00:06:07,734 --> 00:06:10,912
The point is not to think alone.

108
00:06:10,992 --> 00:06:16,440
A good model can widen the room: more
options, clearer tradeoffs, sharper

109
00:06:16,520 --> 00:06:20,153
questions, and a second pass on your
reasoning.

110
00:06:20,233 --> 00:06:22,049
Use it for that.

111
00:06:22,129 --> 00:06:25,307
Use the model for options and tradeoffs.

112
00:06:25,387 --> 00:06:29,019
Keep the goal, evidence, and final
judgment visible.

113
00:06:29,099 --> 00:06:31,823
Before you accept the answer, ask:

114
00:06:31,903 --> 00:06:33,719
What is the goal?

115
00:06:33,799 --> 00:06:36,523
What would ground this in reality?

116
00:06:36,603 --> 00:06:39,328
What belongs to me to choose?

117
00:06:39,408 --> 00:06:42,586
Let the AI help you see more.

118
00:06:42,666 --> 00:06:46,752
Do not let it decide what seeing is for.
